Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Pop
them onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with oil, season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}, then toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, cut the @mature cheddar cheese{30%grams} into even chunks, 1 per
person. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

In a large #bowl{}, combine the @sun-dried tomato paste{25%grams}, garlic and
@breadcrumbs{10%grams}, then add the @British beef and pork mince{240%grams}.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then mix together with your hands.

Roll the mince into even-sized balls. Shape into 2cm thick burgers around a
chunk of cheese, ensuring they're well sealed, 1 per person.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Pop the burgers onto one side of a baking tray and lay the
@British streaky bacon{4%rashers} in a single layer alongside (use another
tray if necessary).

Bake on the middle shelf of your oven until cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle. Cook bacon
> thoroughly.

When the wedges, bacon and burgers are almost cooked, halve the
@burger buns{2}.

Pop onto a baking tray and into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

== Assembly ==

When everything's ready, spread some @mayonnaise{2%tbsp} over the bun bases.
Top with the burgers, crispy bacon and a handful of @pea shoots{40%grams}.

> TIP: Scoop up any escaped cheese from the baking tray and pile on top.

Add the remaining pea shoots to your plates and drizzle over the
@balsamic glaze{12%milliliters}.

Serve your melt in the middle burgers with the wedges and salad alongside.

Enjoy!